.SH FLEET MANAGER (Ansible Cluster Engine)

The
.B fleet
sub-module provides a lightweight, centralized server orchestration and automation engine built directly into One-Click. 

Using Ansible as its foundational execution engine, it enforces a highly secure "Hub-and-Spoke" mesh topology. All cluster nodes retain strict peer-to-peer communication channels, but public exposure is strictly limited: only the central controller maintains broad public access, while remaining target nodes are locked down completely on all non-essential administrative layers.

.SS FLEET SUBCOMMANDS

.TP
.B init
Initialize fleet configuration patterns, establish workspace directory trees, and safely generate localized SSH automation cryptographic keys.
.TP
.B add <ip> <host> [port]
Register a new remote target system into fleet tracking configurations, passing administrative automation parameters.
.TP
.B remove | rm <host>
Deletes a tracked remote server profile permanently from the fleet tracking environment.
.TP
.B verify
Test multi-node SSH connectivity and runtime capability simultaneously on all tracked targets via an internal Ansible ping check execution block.
.TP
.B update-keys
Gracefully rotate administration SSH communication keys on both the central controller and active fleet members synchronously without dropping management handles.
.TP
.B update
Run the 'one-click update' execution block simultaneously across all active, reachable fleet targets.
.TP
.B audit
Gather real-time hardware architecture, storage map profiles, and network footprint parameters across the cluster, serializing results locally into JSON payloads.
.TP
.B bench
Execute asynchronous hardware stress benchmarks across multiple hosts simultaneously and fetch complete performance payload matrices back to the controller.
.TP
.B rule-engine | engine
Orchestrate uniform or host-targeted firewall controls across the fleet using centralized security constraints.
.TP
.B dir <host> <directory>
List remote filesystems and operational directory status on target fleet members.
.TP
.B put <host> <src> <dest>
Upload a local file or complete workspace directory payload asynchronously from the controller up to a targeted remote host node.
.TP
.B get <host> <src> <dest>
Download a file away from a remote host node down to the local controller tracking space.
.TP
.B raw <host> '<command>'
Bypass playbooks to execute direct shell configurations instantly inside a secure remote login terminal wrapper.
.TP
.B clone-site <site> <peer>
Clone static sites, WordPress setups, Nextcloud deployments, and application runtimes to a target fleet peer node using automated workflows under the hood.
.TP
.B restore-site <site> <peer>
Restore static, WordPress, Nextcloud, and full application infrastructure deployments across selected fleet targets.

.SH VIRTUAL PRIVATE SERVER (VPS) ENGINE

Using the underlying fleet engine infrastructure, the
.B --vps
arm transforms the controller and its fleet members into an orchestrated hypervisor layer. It allows for rapid creation, configuration, and state management of KVM Virtual Machines. 

Newly provisioned instances can be dynamically joined into the orchestration pool as managed endpoints. For targets deployed inside restricted NAT environments, secure access is bridged seamlessly using the built-in tunnel interface.

.SS VPS MANAGEMENT INTERFACE

.TP
.B create
Provision a new kernel-isolated KVM virtual machine inside the selected hypervisor peer node or localized controller context.
.TP
.B delete
Gracefully wipe a KVM instance and purge its underlying block allocation mappings on the target hypervisor host.
.TP
.B edit
Modify hardware profiles or runtime configuration values for an existing virtual machine instance.
.TP
.B reinstall
Wipe and reinstall the operating system environment of a target fleet virtual machine peer node.
.TP
.B snapshot
Create, list, restore, or discard point-in-time state captures of target guest virtual machines.
.TP
.B backup
Create, restore, and discard local and remote backups of target guest virtual machines.
.TP
.B patch
Apply operating system patches and platform level updates across target guest nodes or the entirety of your compute fleet.
.TP
.B migrate
Live or cold migrate a running virtual instance off its current host machine onto a separate peer hypervisor node.
.TP
.B start
Power on a stopped guest VPS instance.
.TP
.B stop
Gracefully or forcefully halt a running guest VPS instance.
.TP
.B view
Examine and list all active snapshots tracking against target virtual machines.

.SS PARAMETERS & CAPABILITIES

The following operational switches constrain core VPS behaviors:
.TP
.BI \-n, "\-\-name"
Explicit handle identifier for the virtual instance.
.TP
.BI \-t, "\-\-target"
Designate which active fleet member or hypervisor node to pin the virtualization workspace onto.
.TP
.BI \-m, "\-\-mode"
Set network topology profile. Valid selections are
.B nat
(isolated wireguard overlay) or
.B public
(directly routable public address space).
.TP
.BI \-i, "\-\-image"
Target ISO or cloud OS metadata image. The platform resolves shorthand labels (e.g., ubuntu24) automatically.
.TP
.BI \-d, "\-\-disk"
Total block storage disk quota allocation string (e.g., 20G).
.TP
.BI \-c, "\-\-cpu"
Count of virtualized vCPU cores pinned to the compute profile.
.TP
.BI \-r, "\-\-ram"
System memory sizing string (e.g., 2G).
.TP
.BI \-p, "\-\-ip"
Flag mapping instruction to assign and bind public-facing IP allocation routes directly to the interface.
.TP
.BI \-w, "\-\-password"
Assign explicit passwords to administrative user environments during setup tasks.
.TP
.BI \-l, "\-\-language"
Explicitly define regional localization settings for targeted Windows installations.

.SS TUNNELING ACROSS NAT
To establish clean terminal configurations into hypervisor targets restricted behind NAT mappings, execute:
.IP
.B one-click \-\-ssh <peer\-name>

.SH PROXY ENGINE

The
.B \-\-proxy
sub-system deploys and coordinates HAProxy configurations running directly at the edge of the hypervisor interface. It acts as an ingress layer, taking public traffic requests from the open internet and routing them securely across network constraints to backend nodes inside isolated, non-routable WireGuard NAT environments.

.SS PROXY CONTROL OPTIONS

.TP
.BI \-t, "\-\-target"
Define the destination namespace name representing the target NAT virtual machine.
.TP
.BI \-w, "\-\-website"
The Fully Qualified Domain Name (FQDN) assigned to capture and route incoming public HTTP/HTTPS payloads.
.TP
.BI \-c, "\-\-proto"
Traffic enforcement mechanism scheme (e.g., http, https, tcp).
.TP
.BI \-s, "\-\-source"
The active local network port receiving applications listening inside the destination virtual guest environment.
.TP
.BI \-p, "\-\-port"
The public-facing listener port bound onto the hypervisor host edge infrastructure to swallow and pass traffic.

.SH WIREGUARD MESH ENGINE

The
.B \-\-wireguard
sub-module manages secure internal networking. It carves an isolated /24 overlay subnet slice cleanly away from the backend mesh backplane, generating modern cryptographic tunnel configurations. This allows external customer environments and client devices to route securely into the isolated fleet array.

.SS WIREGUARD MESH COMMANDS

.TP
.B add-user
Create and register cryptographic key profile footprints to append a new client node device safely into the private mesh layer.
.TP
.B delete-user
Revoke and purge a client profile footprint to instantly block mesh access paths.
.TP
.B view
Examine real-time connections, peer tracking metadata, and health stats across active mesh profiles.

.SH DNS MANAGER & REPLICATION

The built-in DNS Manager facilitates naming resolution paths across the network topology. It orchestrates BIND server engines across all tracked fleet peers, providing zone configuration profiles and automating secure zone replication hooks across peers instantly whenever adjustments are recorded. This enables distributed naming availability across independent geographic clusters without risking master sync synchronization drifts.

.SH WORDPRESS & WEB PROVISIONING ENGINE

The
.B One-Click WordPress module
is a system-level site provisioning engine that deploys fully isolated web applications with automated webserver, database, SSL, and runtime configuration.

It does not function as a simple WordPress installer. Instead, it orchestrates full-stack environment creation for each domain, treating every site as an independent system service.

.SS CORE FUNCTIONAL MODEL

Each deployment is treated as a fully isolated application unit:

.IP \(bu 2
Dedicated Linux system user per site
.IP \(bu 2
Dedicated PHP-FPM pool per domain
.IP \(bu 2
Independent webserver virtual host (Nginx or Apache)
.IP \(bu 2
Dedicated database per site with unique credentials
.IP \(bu 2
Filesystem isolation under /etc/one-click
.IP \(bu 2
Systemd-based resource control per site

.PP
This design avoids containerization while still enforcing strong multi-site isolation.

.SS WHAT THE SYSTEM ACTUALLY DOES

The WordPress module is responsible for:

.IP \(bu 2
Provisioning webserver configurations (vhosts, document roots)
.IP \(bu 2
Creating and configuring databases dynamically
.IP \(bu 2
Installing WordPress via WP-CLI automation
.IP \(bu 2
Generating secure admin credentials
.IP \(bu 2
Applying PHP-FPM pool isolation per domain
.IP \(bu 2
Managing SSL certificates via Certbot
.IP \(bu 2
Applying system-level resource constraints (systemd slices)
.IP \(bu 2
Handling backup lifecycle per site
.IP \(bu 2
Maintaining deterministic directory structure

.SS FILESYSTEM STRUCTURE

All sites are deployed under:

.RS
/etc/one-click/wordpress/<domain>/www
.RE

Backups:

.RS
/etc/one-click/wordpress/backups/<domain>
.RE

SSL certificates:

.RS
/etc/letsencrypt/live/<domain>
.RE

.SS INSTALLATION BEHAVIOR

The installer performs a deterministic provisioning pipeline:

.IP "1."
Validates domain format and checks DNS resolution (root + www expected)

.IP "2."
Installs or verifies required dependencies (web server, PHP, MariaDB, certbot, WP-CLI)

.IP "3."
Creates isolated system user and directory structure for the domain

.IP "4."
Configures selected webserver (Nginx or Apache virtual host)

.IP "5."
Creates dedicated database and credentials per site

.IP "6."
Downloads and installs WordPress using WP-CLI

.IP "7."
Generates wp-config.php with secure salts and DB bindings

.IP "8."
Creates WordPress admin user with enforced password policy

.IP "9."
Optionally installs performance/security plugins (e.g. caching)

.IP "10."
Attempts automatic SSL provisioning via Certbot

.IP "11."
Rewrites WordPress URLs to HTTPS if SSL succeeds

.PP
If SSL fails, the site remains operational over HTTP with retry options available or the ability to issue a self signed certificate.

.SS COMMAND INTERFACE

.RS
.B one-click --wp-create
.RE

Creates a new fully isolated WordPress site.

.RS
.B one-click --ssl <domain>
.RE

Provisions or renews SSL certificates for an existing site.

.SS ISOLATION MODEL

Each site is isolated at multiple layers:

.IP \(bu 2
Process isolation via PHP-FPM pools
.IP \(bu 2
User-level isolation via Linux system users
.IP \(bu 2
Network exposure controlled via webserver virtual hosts
.IP \(bu 2
Resource isolation via systemd slices
.IP \(bu 2
Credential isolation via per-site database users

.SS BACKUP SYSTEM

Each site includes automated backup capability:

.IP \(bu 2
Filesystem snapshot of WordPress installation
.IP \(bu 2
Database export per domain
.IP \(bu 2
Configuration metadata preservation
.IP \(bu 2
Timestamped backup rotation per domain

.SS SSL MANAGEMENT

SSL provisioning is handled through Certbot automation:

.IP \(bu 2
Domain validation via DNS resolution
.IP \(bu 2
Certificate issuance or renewal
.IP \(bu 2
Webserver reload after certificate install
.IP \(bu 2
Automatic HTTPS URL migration inside WordPress

.SS DESIGN CHARACTERISTICS

This system differs from typical WordPress installers:

.IP \(bu 2
Not shared-hosting based
.IP \(bu 2
Not container-based (no Docker dependency)
.IP \(bu 2
Not single-directory deployment model
.IP \(bu 2
Not manual webserver configuration
.IP \(bu 2
Fully automated system-level provisioning engine

.SS EXAMPLES

Create a new site:

.RS
.B one-click --wp-create
.RE

Provision SSL:

.RS
.B one-click --wp-ssl example.com
.RE

.SS FAILURE HANDLING

The system includes recovery behavior:

.IP \(bu 2
Partial installs are handled safely
.IP \(bu 2
Database creation rollback where possible
.IP \(bu 2
Installation logs preserved for debugging
.IP \(bu 2
SSL failure does not block site deployment

.SH RULE-ENGINE (Firewall Management)

.B Rule-engine
is a high-level firewall orchestration layer that translates human-readable intent into safe, backend-specific firewall rules.

It supports multiple firewall backends including
.B iptables
and
.B nftables,
while maintaining a unified interface and enforcing strict safety guarantees.

Unlike traditional firewall tools, rule-engine focuses on:

.IP \(bu 2
Human-readable rule definitions
.IP \(bu 2
Automatic validation and duplicate prevention
.IP \(bu 2
Built-in intrusion detection and mitigation
.IP \(bu 2
Transactional rule application with rollback protection
.IP \(bu 2
Full audit logging and traceability

.SS RULE PARSING

User input is parsed into structured components:

.IP \(bu 2
Source (IP address or alias)
.IP \(bu 2
Protocol (tcp, udp, icmp, any)
.IP \(bu 2
Port or port range
.IP \(bu 2
Action (ACCEPT, DROP, REJECT, LOG)

The engine translates these into backend-specific firewall commands and stages them for validation prior to execution.

Before any rule is applied:

.IP "1."
Syntax validation and duplicate detection are performed
.IP "2."
Sensitive services (e.g., SSH, DNS, HTTP) are checked for risk impact
.IP "3."
A preview of the generated firewall commands is displayed to the user

No rule is executed without explicit confirmation.

.SS TRANSACTIONAL RULE APPLICATION

Firewall changes are executed using a transactional model designed to prevent lockout.

.IP "1. Dry Run"
Rules are simulated without modifying the active firewall. Critical services are validated.

.IP "2. Pending Apply"
Rules are applied to the live firewall in a temporary state.

.IP "3. Confirmation Window"
The user has
.B 15 seconds
to confirm connectivity after application.

.IP "4. Auto-Rollback"
If confirmation is not received, all changes are automatically reverted.

This ensures remote access cannot be permanently disrupted by misconfiguration.

.SS AUTOMATED MITIGATION (GUARD MODE)

Rule-engine includes a real-time intrusion detection and response system.

.TP
.B Passive Mode
Events are logged only. No blocking is performed.

.TP
.B Automatic Mode
Detected threats trigger immediate firewall enforcement.

Detected behaviors include:

.IP \(bu 2
SSH brute-force attempts (via system logs)
.IP \(bu 2
Abnormal connection spikes (DDoS pattern detection)

When thresholds are exceeded:

.IP \(bu 2
The source IP is blocked using firewall rules
.IP \(bu 2
A temporary timeout is applied
.IP \(bu 2
The event is logged for audit purposes

Example:
.IP \(bu 2
5 failed SSH logins → IP blocked for 300 seconds

.SS TEMPORARY BLOCKING

The engine supports time-based firewall rules.

When a block is applied:

.IP \(bu 2
The rule is inserted immediately into the firewall
.IP \(bu 2
A background process tracks expiration time
.IP \(bu 2
The rule is automatically removed when the timeout expires

All actions are recorded in the mitigation history log.

.SS REAL-TIME MONITORING

The system continuously monitors:

.IP \(bu 2
System authentication logs (SSH failures, auth errors)
.IP \(bu 2
Active network connections (via ss/netstat)

Monitoring daemons run in the background and feed events into the mitigation engine.

.SS AUDITING AND VISIBILITY

Rule-engine provides multiple audit views:

.TP
.B Rule Traversal
Displays active firewall rules across all tables and chains, including packet counters and blocked traffic totals.

.TP
.B Mitigation Logs
Shows recent automated actions, including:
.IP \(bu 2
Timestamp
.IP \(bu 2
Source IP
.IP \(bu 2
Action taken
.IP \(bu 2
Duration or reason

.TP
.B Attack Statistics
Aggregates repeated offenders, showing:
.IP \(bu 2
Attempt counts
.IP \(bu 2
Targeted services or users
.IP \(bu 2
Last-seen timestamps

.TP
.B Global Banlist
Combines RuleEngine bans with external systems such as Fail2Ban.

.SS BACKUP AND RESTORE

Firewall configurations can be exported and restored.

.IP \(bu 2
Backups capture full firewall state of the active backend
.IP \(bu 2
Restore operations flush existing rules before applying backup
.IP \(bu 2
Backend type is automatically detected from backup metadata

.SS ALIAS MANAGEMENT

Aliases allow multiple IP addresses to be grouped under a single identifier.

Example:
.IP \(bu 2
"office" → 192.168.1.10, 192.168.1.11

Aliases can be used in place of raw IP addresses in firewall rules.

Features:

.IP \(bu 2
Create and delete aliases
.IP \(bu 2
Add or remove IPs from existing aliases
.IP \(bu 2
Persistent storage via configuration files

.SS SAFETY FEATURES

The rule-engine enforces multiple safety layers:

.TP
.B Duplicate Prevention
Prevents redundant rule insertion.

.TP
.B Sensitive Port Protection
Warns before modifying critical services (e.g., SSH).

.TP
.B Lockout Protection
Uses simulation and rollback to prevent loss of connectivity.

.TP
.B Rule Deduplication
Detects and optionally removes duplicate firewall entries.

.SS INTEGRATION

Rule-engine integrates with:

.IP \(bu 2
Fail2Ban (jail creation and ban visibility)
.IP \(bu 2
AbuseIPDB (IP reputation lookup and reporting)
.IP \(bu 2
System logging via journalctl

.SS EXAMPLES

Block SSH access from an IP:
.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "drop ssh from 1.2.3.4"

Allow HTTP traffic:
.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "allow http"

View firewall rules:
.IP
.B one-click rule-engine show

View security audit logs:
.IP
.B one-click rule-engine audit

.SS SUMMARY

The rule-engine combines firewall management, intrusion detection, and automated mitigation into a unified system.

It is designed to:

.IP \(bu 2
Simplify firewall administration
.IP \(bu 2
Prevent misconfiguration and lockouts
.IP \(bu 2
Provide real-time threat response
.IP \(bu 2
Ensure full auditability of all actions

