.B one-click rule-engine "audit banlist"
Show all banned IPs (RuleEngine + Fail2Ban)

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "audit lookup 8.8.8.8"
Check IP reputation via AbuseIPDB

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "audit scan"
Run system integrity scan

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "audit scan --deep"
Full filesystem and binary scan

.SS ATTACK MITIGATION

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "audit block 12"
Temporarily block attacker ID 12

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "audit block 12 perm"
Permanently ban attacker

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "audit unblock 12"
Remove block from attacker

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "audit block 5 dur=300"
Block attacker for 5 minutes

.SS SYSTEM MANAGEMENT

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "show"
Display current firewall rules

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "open all"
Show full ruleset across tables

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "flush all"
Clear entire firewall configuration

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "flush filter"
Clear specific table

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "backup"
Save current firewall configuration

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "restore"
Restore previous firewall state

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "mask"
Enable NAT masquerading

.SS SAFETY AND TESTING

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine --dry-run "allow 443"
Simulate HTTPS rule without applying

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine --dry-run "drop ssh from 10.0.0.5"
Test firewall impact safely

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "sensitive 22 3306"
Mark SSH and MySQL as critical ports

.SS COMPLEX REAL-WORLD EXAMPLES

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "allow ssh from office and allow https"
Allow secure admin + web traffic

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "allow http from office and drop all from 1.2.3.4"
Mixed whitelist + blacklist rule

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "alias-create trusted 10.0.0.1 10.0.0.2 and allow ssh from trusted"
Create trusted network and allow access

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "audit ssh and audit block 7 perm"
Inspect attack and permanently ban

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "audit scan --deep and backup"
Run security scan and backup firewall

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "allow range 1000-2000 and drop smtp"
Open app range but block mail

.SS CHAINED NATURAL LANGUAGE COMMANDS

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "allow ssh and drop smtp and allow https"
Multiple independent actions in one request

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "allow 80, allow 443, allow 22"
Comma-separated batch rules

.IP
.B one-click rule-engine "drop ssh from 1.2.3.4 and audit block 1 perm"
Block attacker and permanently ban

.SH REINSTALL

The
.B reinstall
command performs a complete operating system reinstallation.

.B WARNING:
This operation destroys all existing data on the target system.

.PP
Features:

.IP \(bu 2
Network- and cloud-based installation

.IP \(bu 2
Supports Linux and Windows targets

.IP \(bu 2
Independent of current system state

.IP \(bu 2
Suitable for recovery or reprovisioning

.PP
Supported target systems and versions:

.TS
tab(|) box;
l l l l
l l l l.
System | Version | Memory | Disk
_
Alpine | 3.20, 3.21, 3.22, 3.23 | 256 MB | 1 GB
Debian | 9–13 | 256 MB | 1–1.5 GB ^
Kali | Rolling | 256 MB | 1–1.5 GB ^
Ubuntu | 16.04 LTS–24.04 LTS, 25.10 | 512 MB * | 2 GB
Anolis | 7, 8, 23 | 512 MB * | 5 GB
RHEL / AlmaLinux / Rocky / Oracle | 8–10 | 512 MB * | 5 GB
OpenCloudOS | 8, 9, Stream 23 | 512 MB * | 5 GB
CentOS Stream | 9, 10 | 512 MB * | 5 GB
Fedora | 42, 43 | 512 MB * | 5 GB
openEuler | 20.03–24.03 LTS, 25.09 | 512 MB * | 5 GB
openSUSE | Leap 15.6, 16.0, Tumbleweed | 512 MB * | 5 GB
NixOS | 25.11 | 512 MB | 5 GB
Arch | Rolling | 512 MB | 5 GB
Gentoo | Rolling | 512 MB | 5 GB
AOSC OS | Rolling | 512 MB | 5 GB
fnOS | 1 | 512 MB | 8 GB
Windows (DD) | Any | 512 MB | Depends on image
Windows (ISO) | Vista, 7, 8.x / Server 2008–2012 R2 | 512 MB | 25 GB
Windows (ISO) | 10, 11 / Server 2016–2025 | 1 GB | 25 GB
.TE

.PP
* Installation using cloud images rather than traditional network installation.  

^ Either:  
.br
256 MB memory + 1.5 GB disk  
.br
or  
.br
512 MB memory + 1 GB disk  

.SH REINSTALL NOTES

.IP \(bu 2
Target username is
.B root.
The installer prompts for a password; if left blank, a random one is generated.

.IP \(bu 2
When installing the latest version, specifying the version number is optional.

.IP \(bu 2
Maximizes disk usage: no separate boot partition (except Fedora) and no swap partition.

.IP \(bu 2
Automatically selects optimized kernels based on machine type (Cloud or HWE kernels).

.IP \(bu 2
Red Hat installations require a qcow2 image link from:
.br
https://access.redhat.com/downloads/content/rhel  
Other RHEL-based qcow2 images (e.g., Alibaba Cloud Linux, TencentOS Server) are also supported.

.IP \(bu 2
After reinstallation, if changing SSH port or switching to key-based authentication, also update:
.br
.I /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/

.IP \(bu 2
Supports raw and fixed-size VHD images. Supported formats:  
.br
.I .gz, .xz, .zst, .tar, .tar.gz, .tar.xz, .tar.zst

.IP \(bu 2
Windows deployment notes:  
.br
System disk is automatically expanded.  
.br
Static IPs are configured automatically.  
.br
Initial configuration may take several minutes after first boot.

.IP \(bu 2
Linux deployment notes:  
.br
Installer preserves all contents of the provided image; it does not modify it.

.SH BACKUP

The
.B backup
command performs incremental backups using multiple methods:

.IP \(bu 2
Local rsync snapshots

.IP \(bu 2
Remote rsync over SSH

.IP \(bu 2
Cloud storage via rclone

.PP
Backups are incremental, efficient, and designed for rapid restoration.

.PP
Key features:

.IP \(bu 2
Block-level incremental transfers using the rsync delta algorithm

.IP \(bu 2
Snapshot-style backups with hard links to minimize disk usage

.IP \(bu 2
Support for local, remote, and cloud destinations

.IP \(bu 2
Bandwidth-efficient operation for limited networks

.IP \(bu 2
Fast restoration with minimal reconstruction

.IP \(bu 2
Preserves permissions, ownership, timestamps, and symbolic links

.IP \(bu 2
Supports full system or partial directory backups

.IP \(bu 2
Safe operation on live systems without downtime

.SH BACKUP DESTINATIONS

.TS
tab(|) box;
l l.
Destination | Method
_
Local disk | rsync snapshot
Remote server | rsync over SSH
Cloud storage | rclone supported providers
Network storage | SSH, NFS, or mounted filesystem
External disk | Direct filesystem backup
.TE

.SH BACKUP CLOUD PROVIDERS

Supported cloud providers (via rclone) include, but are not limited to:

.IP \(bu 2
Amazon S3

.IP \(bu 2
Backblaze B2

.IP \(bu 2
Google Cloud Storage

.IP \(bu 2
Microsoft Azure Blob Storage

.IP \(bu 2
Dropbox

.IP \(bu 2
Wasabi

.IP \(bu 2
Cloudflare R2

.IP \(bu 2
Any provider supported by rclone

.SH BACKUP BEHAVIOR

.IP \(bu 2
Initial backup creates a full snapshot

.IP \(bu 2
Subsequent backups transfer only changed files

.IP \(bu 2
Unchanged files are referenced using hard links

.IP \(bu 2
Deleted files may remain in previous snapshots

.IP \(bu 2
Backup integrity is verified during transfer

.SH RESTORE CAPABILITIES

.IP \(bu 2
Individual file restore

.IP \(bu 2
Directory restore

.IP \(bu 2
Full system restore

.IP \(bu 2
Bare-metal recovery support

.SH BACKUP REQUIREMENTS

.TS
tab(|) box;
l l.
Component | Requirement
_
Local backup | rsync installed
Remote backup | rsync and SSH access
Cloud backup | rclone configured remote
Filesystem | Supports permissions and hard links
.TE

.SH SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS

.IP \(bu 2
Remote transfers use SSH encryption

.IP \(bu 2
Cloud transfers leverage provider-supported encryption

.IP \(bu 2
Authentication is handled via SSH keys or rclone configuration

.IP \(bu 2
Backup data remains unchanged unless explicitly modified

.PP
The
.B backup
command is suitable for routine system protection, migration preparation, and disaster recovery.

.SH BOOT-RECOVERY

The
.B boot-recovery
command creates and restores boot-critical snapshots.

.PP
Components included:

.IP \(bu 2
Bootloader – preserves GRUB or alternative bootloader configuration and binaries

.IP \(bu 2
Kernel – captures the currently active kernel image(s)

.IP \(bu 2
Initramfs – stores the initial RAM filesystem used during boot

.IP \(bu 2
Root filesystem metadata – maintains essential filesystem structures required for boot

.PP
Typical use cases:

.IP \(bu 2
Recover from boot failures caused by kernel or bootloader corruption

.IP \(bu 2
Test new kernels or boot configurations without risking system unbootability

.IP \(bu 2
Perform safe rollback after failed updates or misconfigured boot parameters

.PP
Operation details:

.IP \(bu 2
Snapshots may be stored locally or on remote locations

.IP \(bu 2
Restoration overwrites only boot-critical components

.IP \(bu 2
User data outside boot-critical areas is preserved

.IP \(bu 2
Supports incremental snapshotting to reduce storage usage

.PP
Security and safety:

.IP \(bu 2
Root privileges are required to create or restore snapshots

.IP \(bu 2
Restoration is destructive to boot components; verify backups first

.IP \(bu 2
Compatible with
.B backup
snapshots for coordinated system recovery

.SH REPAIR

The
.B repair
command restores network configurations from snapshots.

.PP
Recovery scenarios:

.IP \(bu 2
Firewall misconfiguration – restores iptables, nftables, or equivalent rules

.IP \(bu 2
Interface errors – resets network interfaces to the snapshot state

.IP \(bu 2
Routing failures – restores static routes, gateways, and routing tables

.PP
Ideal usage:

.IP \(bu 2
Remote servers with limited manual access

.IP \(bu 2
Systems requiring high network uptime and connectivity

.IP \(bu 2
Recovery from configuration errors without full system reinstall

.PP
Operation details:

.IP \(bu 2
Snapshots may be stored locally or remotely

.IP \(bu 2
Restoration affects only network configuration files and runtime settings

.IP \(bu 2
Supports interface-level or system-wide restores

.IP \(bu 2
Incremental restores prevent overwriting unrelated settings

.PP
Security and safety:

.IP \(bu 2
Root privileges are required

.IP \(bu 2
Verify backup integrity to avoid restoring misconfigured snapshots

.IP \(bu 2
For remote systems, consider temporary console or alternative access to avoid lockout

.PP
The
.B repair
command ensures network stability and fast recovery from misconfigurations.

.SH MIGRATE

The
.B migrate
command transfers entire systems between hosts or storage.

.PP
Supported migration methods:

.TP
.B dd
Block-level cloning – creates an exact disk image including all partitions, bootloader, and filesystem structures

.TP
.B rsync
File-level migration – copies files and directories while preserving permissions, ownership, and timestamps

.PP
Use cases:

.IP \(bu 2
Server replacement – migrate systems to new hardware with minimal downtime

.IP \(bu 2
Failover preparation – replicate systems for high availability or disaster recovery

.IP \(bu 2
Infrastructure migration – move servers to new hosts, data centers, or cloud environments

.PP
Operation details:

.IP \(bu 2
Supports local, remote, and network-based migrations via SSH or mounted storage

.IP \(bu 2
Incremental file-level migrations reduce transfer time

.IP \(bu 2
Preserves system configuration, installed packages, and user data

.IP \(bu 2
Bare-metal restores supported via dd images or rsync snapshots

.PP
Safety and security:

.IP \(bu 2
Root privileges are required for full system migration

.IP \(bu 2
Ensure target storage has sufficient space

.IP \(bu 2
Verify network reliability when migrating remote systems

.IP \(bu 2
Block-level cloning overwrites all target disk contents – use with extreme caution

.SH BENCH

The
.B bench
command (also referred to as
.BR "one-click bench" " (OCB)" )
runs a comprehensive system benchmark suite that evaluates server performance across CPU, memory, disk, and network subsystems.

.PP
OCB is suitable for:

.IP \(bu 2
VPS performance validation

.IP \(bu 2
Dedicated server benchmarking

.IP \(bu 2
Cloud instance comparison

.IP \(bu 2
Pre-deployment verification

.IP \(bu 2
Post-migration performance checks

.PP
Benchmark components:

.IP \(bu 2
CPU performance – multi-threaded and single-threaded computational tests

.IP \(bu 2
Memory performance – sequential read and write bandwidth measurements

.IP \(bu 2
Disk performance – sequential and random I/O throughput and latency

.IP \(bu 2
Network latency – multi-target latency testing, sorted by lowest response time

.IP \(bu 2
System inspection – kernel, virtualization detection, CPU model, and architecture

.PP
Operation details:

.IP \(bu 2
Targets are latency-tested and sorted by lowest round-trip time before bandwidth tests

.IP \(bu 2
Tests are executed sequentially for consistency

.IP \(bu 2
Results are displayed in structured tables

.IP \(bu 2
Optional color-coded scoring for quick performance assessment

.IP \(bu 2
Non-destructive and safe for production systems

.PP
Dependencies are installed automatically if missing, and OCB runs inside a
.BR tmux (1)
session when executed interactively to prevent interruption.

.PP
The benchmark does not modify system configuration or persist changes.

.PP
Example:

.RS
.B one-click bench
.RE

.SH SYS-INFO/SYSTEM

The
.B sys-info
command displays live system statistics, providing a real-time overview.

.PP
Monitored metrics:

.IP \(bu 2
CPU usage – overall and per-core utilization

.IP \(bu 2
Memory usage – RAM and swap consumption

.IP \(bu 2
Disk usage – filesystem space and I/O statistics

.IP \(bu 2
Network statistics – bandwidth usage and interface traffic

.IP \(bu 2
Load average – 1, 5, and 15 minute system load metrics

.PP
Additional features:

.IP \(bu 2
Real-time updates with configurable refresh intervals

.IP \(bu 2
Sortable and filterable per CPU, memory, or disk device

.IP \(bu 2
Optional color-coded output for quick status assessment

.IP \(bu 2
Supports remote monitoring via SSH

.PP
Provides functionality similar to
.BR top (1)
and
.BR htop (1)
while integrating with other system management utilities.

.SH CRON

The
.B cron
command provides an interface for scheduling automation tasks.

.PP
Supported tasks:

.IP \(bu 2
Scheduled backups – automatically run
.B backup
jobs

.IP \(bu 2
Maintenance automation – perform routine cleanup, updates, or maintenance

.IP \(bu 2
Snapshot rotation – manage retention of
.B backup
and
.B boot-recovery
snapshots

.PP
Additional features:

.IP \(bu 2
Flexible scheduling using standard cron syntax or simplified intervals

.IP \(bu 2
Supports logging of task output for auditing

.IP \(bu 2
Integration with
.B backup,
.B boot-recovery,
and
.B repair
for automated system management

.IP \(bu 2
Safe execution with defined privileges to prevent accidental damage

.SH MIGRATE

The
.B migrate
command transfers One-Click toolkit configuration between systems.

.PP
Migrated components:

.IP \(bu 2
User configuration

.IP \(bu 2
Rule-engine aliases

.IP \(bu 2
Firewall backups

.IP \(bu 2
Scheduled automation tasks (cron)

.PP
Migration archives are compressed tar files that can be transferred and imported on a target system.

.SH USAGE

.TS
tab(|) box;
l l.
Command | Description
_
one-click migrate export | Export current configuration to a migration archive
one-click migrate import <archive> | Import configuration from a migration archive
one-click migrate to <user@host> | Send migration archive to a remote host and optionally import
.TE

.PP
Archive contents:

.IP \(bu 2
One-Click configuration directory (/etc/one-click)

.IP \(bu 2
Crontab entries for the current user

.IP \(bu 2
Scanner cron jobs in /etc/cron.d/one-click-scanner

.SH EXAMPLES

Export configuration locally:

.RS
.B one-click migrate export
.RE

Import configuration from a local archive:

.RS
.B one-click migrate import /etc/one-click/migrate/one-click-migration-20260315162903.tar.gz
.RE

Send and import migration archive on a remote host:

.RS
.B one-click migrate to root@server2
.RE

.PP
During remote migration:

.IP \(bu 2
The target system is checked for One-Click and installed automatically if missing

.IP \(bu 2
User may be prompted to confirm import

.IP \(bu 2
SSH keys or password authentication is required

.IP \(bu 2
Target host must allow SSH and have basic tools (bash, tar, curl)

.IP \(bu 2
Migration is safe and does not overwrite unrelated system files

.SH UNINSTALL

The
.B uninstall
command removes the One-Click tool and all associated files from the system.

.PP
Components removed:

.IP \(bu 2
Installed scripts – all executable binaries and supporting scripts

.IP \(bu 2
Configuration files – system-wide and user-specific settings

.IP \(bu 2
Cron jobs – any scheduled automation tasks created by the tool

.IP \(bu 2
Logs – log files and temporary data generated during operation

.PP
Operation details:

.IP \(bu 2
Requires root privileges to remove system-wide files and cron entries

.IP \(bu 2
Performs cleanup safely without affecting unrelated files

.IP \(bu 2
Leaves no residual data when executed correctly

.IP \(bu 2
Can be used to prepare the system for reinstallation or migration

.SH FILES

.TP
.I /etc/one-click/
Configuration directory storing system and user settings

.TP
.I /var/log/one-click/
Log directory for command execution and system events

.TP
.I /usr/local/bin/one-click
Executable for the One-Click tool

.TP
.I /usr/local/share/man/man8/one-click.8
Man page for reference and usage documentation

.SH ENVIRONMENT

.TP
.B TMUX
Used automatically to manage persistent sessions when running commands interactively

.TP
.B HOME
User home directory; used to store user-specific configuration and temporary data

.SH SECURITY

The
.B one-click
tool requires root privileges for most operations.

.PP
Best practices:

.IP \(bu 2
Verify script source integrity – ensure the tool and updates are obtained from trusted sources

.IP \(bu 2
Review destructive commands before execution – especially
.B reinstall,
.B migrate,
.B repair,
.B \-\-vps delete,
and
.B uninstall

.IP \(bu 2
Maintain backups before reinstall or migration to prevent data loss and allow recovery

.PP
Additional considerations:

.IP \(bu 2
Use secure credentials and SSH keys for remote operations

.IP \(bu 2
Restrict access to system configuration and snapshot directories

.IP \(bu 2
Monitor logs to detect unauthorized or failed operations
